KAGGLE COMPETITION

Welcome to the task of predicting house prices! As a data analyst, my job in this task is to use my skills and expertise to develop a model that accurately predicts the sale price for each house in the test set. In this task, we have been given a set of Ids for houses, and it is my responsibility to predict the corresponding value of the SalePrice variable. With accurate predictions, I can help potential homebuyers make informed decisions, assist real estate agents in pricing their properties, and provide valuable insights to the housing market. The challenge ahead requires a combination of statistical analysis, machine learning algorithms, and a deep understanding of the housing market. Let's get started!

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from scipy import stats
from scipy.stats import norm, skew
%matplotlib inline

import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")

### Importing Train Dataset ####

train_data = pd.read_csv(r"C:\Users\User\Desktop\train_dataset.csv")
# Train Dataset Data Cleaning And Exploration
numeric_features = train_data.select_dtypes(include=np.number).columns
# Filling Missing Values for Numeric Values
for column in numeric_features:
    if train_data[column].isna().sum() > 0:
        column_median = train_data[column].median()
        train_data[column] = train_data[column].fillna(column_median)
# Cleaning Categorical Values
categorical_features = set(train_data.columns) - set(numeric_features)
# Clean Categorical Features Using Mode
electrical_mode = train_data['Electrical'].mode()[0]
train_data['Electrical'] = train_data['Electrical'].fillna(electrical_mode)
fence_mode = train_data['Fence'].mode()[0]
train_data['Fence'] = train_data['Fence'].fillna(fence_mode)
masvnrtype_mode = train_data['MasVnrType'].mode()[0]
train_data['MasVnrType'] = train_data['MasVnrType'].fillna(masvnrtype_mode)
# Clean other Categorical Features Using "NA" Where it's an Option
train_data["FireplaceQu"].fillna(value="NA", inplace=True)
train_data["GarageCond"].fillna(value="NA", inplace=True)
train_data["GarageYrBlt"].fillna(value="NA", inplace=True)
train_data["GarageType"].fillna(value="NA", inplace=True)
train_data["GarageFinish"].fillna(value="NA", inplace=True)
train_data["PoolQC"].fillna(value="NA", inplace=True)
train_data["BsmtQual"].fillna(value="NA", inplace=True)
train_data["GarageQual"].fillna(value="NA", inplace=True)
train_data["Alley"].fillna(value="NA", inplace=True)
train_data["BsmtFinType1"].fillna(value="NA", inplace=True)
train_data["BsmtFinType2"].fillna(value="NA", inplace=True)
train_data["BsmtCond"].fillna(value="NA", inplace=True)
train_data["MiscFeature"].fillna(value="NA", inplace=True)

train_data.loc[(train_data["BsmtExposure"].isna()) & (train_data["TotalBsmtSF"]==936), "BsmtExposure"] = train_data["BsmtExposure"].mode()[0]
train_data["BsmtExposure"].fillna(value="NA", inplace=True)

train_filtered = train_data.loc[train_data["BsmtFinType2"] != 'Unf']
train_data.loc[(train_data["BsmtFinType2"].isna()) & (train_data["BsmtFinSF2"]!=0), "BsmtFinType2"] = train_filtered["BsmtFinType2"].mode()[0]
train_data["BsmtFinType2"].fillna(value="NA", inplace=True)
# One hot Encoding for Categorical Features
for cat_col in categorical_features:
    train_data = pd.concat([train_data, pd.get_dummies(train_data[cat_col])], axis=1)
    train_data = train_data.drop(cat_col, axis=1)

# select the relevant columns
x_labels = ['OverallQual', 'GrLivArea', 'GarageCars', 'TotalBsmtSF', 'FullBath', 'YearBuilt']
y_labels = 'SalePrice'
test_data = test[x_labels]

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
# split the dataset into train and test using the seed 219 to make sure the results are replicable
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    train[x_labels], 
    train[y_labels], 
    test_size=0.25,
    random_state=219
)
In [19]:
from sklearn import linear_model, ensemble
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

#Train linear regression model using log Y
reg = linear_model.LinearRegression().fit(x_train, np.log(y_train))
reg_rmse = mean_squared_error(np.log(y_test), reg.predict(x_test), squared=False)

# Train lasso using log Y
lasso = linear_model.Lasso(alpha=0.04).fit(x_train, np.log(y_train))
lasso_rmse = mean_squared_error(np.log(y_test), lasso.predict(x_test), squared=False)

# Train random forest regressor using log Y
rf = ensemble.RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100).fit(x_train, np.log(y_train))
rf_rmse = mean_squared_error(np.log(y_test), rf.predict(x_test), squared=False)

def choose_best_model(reg_rmse, lasso_rmse, rf_rmse):
    """
    Chooses the best model based on the given RMSE values and returns the corresponding model and RMSE value.
    """
    model_names = ['Linear Regression', 'Lasso Regression', 'Random Forest']
    rmse_values = [reg_rmse, lasso_rmse, rf_rmse]
    best_model_idx = rmse_values.index(min(rmse_values))
    best_model_name = model_names[best_model_idx]
    best_rmse = rmse_values[best_model_idx]
    print(f'Best Model: {best_model_name}\nRMSE Value: {best_rmse}')
    if best_model_idx == 0:
        return reg
    elif best_model_idx == 1:
        return lasso
    else:
        return rf

# Choosing the best model based on RMSE
best_model = choose_best_model(reg_rmse, lasso_rmse, rf_rmse)

Best Model: Linear Regression
RMSE Value: 0.16503167697479132
